## 3) A container works on your laptop but fails in Kubernetes. Why can that happen?

**Answer:**\
This usually happens because the environment in Kubernetes is different
from local Docker. I check:

-   environment variables\
-   ConfigMap values\
-   Secret values\
-   service DNS names\
-   database connectivity\
-   container port vs service port\
-   readiness/liveness probe configuration\
-   image version mismatch\
-   resource limits

I troubleshoot using:

    kubectl logs <pod-name>
    kubectl describe pod <pod-name>
    kubectl exec -it <pod-name> -- sh

A local success only proves the image works in one environment, not that
it is correctly configured in Kubernetes.

